                <td height="622" valign="top" colspan="2" bgcolor="#004142">&nbsp;<table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4"><tr bgcolor="#000000"><td><font color="#FFFFFF"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial" size="6">My characteristics of a good player...</font></td></tr></table><table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0"><tr><td></td><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Rating</Font></TD><TD><IMG SRC="images/a5.gif" BORDER=0><A HREF="articleread.php3?article=121"><IMG SRC="images/aread.GIF" BORDER=0></A><A HREF="articlereview.php3?article=121"><IMG SRC="images/areview.GIF" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Author</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><A HREF="../membercenter/directory/memberpage.php3?member=42">Mike "Iceman" Fitzgerald</A></FONT></TD></TR><!-- 42 --><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Description</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">This is an old article that I touched up to date. Good to dust it off since it still applies.</FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Article</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">To Be a Good Player<br>
By Mike Fitzgerald<br>
<br>
Dedication-<br>
To be a good player you have to want to be a good player. Your showing that you want to be a good player by contributing and reading DeckTech. I consider myself to be a 'good' player. I probably spend at least 10 hours a week searching the Web and various discussion lists looking for new and exciting info and strategies. This number of hours usually doubles and sometimes comes close to tripling when Regionals come around. Take advantage of local gaming nights or , if your like me , try to find a friend and just keep testing new decks against each other with new info you've heard about. What I'm surprised about is that many players don't read Tournament Reports. I think Tournament Reports are where it is at. As long as the writer keeps it interesting and can give a good general description of the decks being played then it is a very valuable metagame asset. The toughest part of dedication is playing when your getting a little bored with the game. I like to create fun decks just for situations to keep me interested. Also , when you've played about 10 games in a row and you keep testing the same decks against each other you get kinda bored quickly too.<br>
<br>
Confidence-<br>
<br>
You shouldn't walk into any game and think your gonna get killed or just wipe the guy off the table. Try to keep an even flow mentality . If your gonna make a mistake just overestimate the opponent instead of underestimating the opponent. Upsets will happen , thats why we play the game instead of giving the player with the higher ranking the win. I get pumped up when I play high rated and considered elite players because I feel something special is gonna happen ( see a new deck style , cards being used like never before , or the chance of me winning ) . I try to use fun decks at tournaments once in awhile to keep myself from worrying about my rating and testing the current scene. Two weeks before Regionals last year I brought 2 decent Hoth Clouds decks and I got smashed by 34 and 35 so then I decided that those weren't gonna cut it so I had to get into the JP / Anti-JP scene. Also , ratings mean very little. Use it to feel proud of yourself once in awhile but don't go to far. Right after Special Edition I played against a player with about a 1420 rating and I managed to battle it out 48 minutes and get a 1 card win. That was the toughest 2 points of my life , against someone in all aspects I was expected to crush off the table ( never mind that is was a HBase deck ;). The first time that I seriously traveled to a top notch tournament ( besides my local area ) was going down to play v. Gabriel Alonso in Miami. I got to play him with my Darkside ( which I considered my best deck at the time -- side note : don't favor one deck over the other ) . I played one of my most memorable games and managed to beat him by 1. He smashed every character I put out while I wasn't knocking any characters of his out. I managed to shake it off and beat him because I kept my head in the game. I truly believe that confidence will help differentiate between players of equal ability ( if there is such a thing ).<br>
<br>
Patience-<br>
<br>
I believe this is the greatest asset to a good player. You and your opponent are both gonna make mistakes. The question is who can exploit the mistake to the fullest for the win. I'm gonna use extreme examples of myself since I know myself the best. I don't like babbling over and over about past Regionals but it helps make my point. In the '97 Dagobah Regionals I was 2-0 and was the 2nd highest player after those 2 games. I played against Brett Helgeson's LS EBO / Droids deck. I was using a Tatooine Drain. I got Vader down to the 4th Marker early and was doing little damage to him ( couldn't find sites ). He was mowing through his deck with How Did We Get Into This Mess , I hadn't seen that before. I got so frustrated because he was just going through his deck at will and I had seen only maybe 20% of the deck and most of it was on the way to the lost pile. Well he had Do or Do not on Table and a grappler on a Sense. Out of feeling helpless I let a Sense fly and cancelled his HDWGITM. He just proceeded to play another. I lost that game by 2 Force. The 2 Force that I lost for wasting that Sense would've saved me the game. Patience. But now well go out of the gloom and doom to the better times. '98 Dagobah Regional. I'm playing v. Rusty Zion's JP Manipulator. He starts with TiNT and has loads of ADT , Voyeurs , and SCrews. He starts right off the bat with manipulation of my interrupt heavy deck. All I do is smirk while he picks works my deck around and tries to get into my head. Somehow I manage to fight him off with the strength of Shocking Info and Grimtaash. I was surprised that I didn't flip out and get impatient because that was a mental exhausting game ( I must've handed my force pile over to ADT about 20 times ) where my patience made the difference.<br>
<br>
Hope this helps you out on your quest to become a better player.<br>
<br>
Iceman/ Mike Fitzgerald / Just smile and nod , baby. Smile and nod</FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP" COLSPAN="2"><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><a href="articles.php3"><img src="images/aback.GIF" border="0"></a><A HREF="articleread.php3?article=121"><IMG SRC="images/aread.GIF" BORDER=0></A><A HREF="articlereview.php3?article=121"><IMG SRC="images/areview.GIF" BORDER=0></A><a href="articleprint.php3?article=121" TARGET="BLANK_"><img src="images/aprint.gif" border="0"></a></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE> </td>
